Here‚Äôs a **Java program** that demonstrates **both method overloading** and **constructor overloading** clearly.

---

### ‚úÖ **Method Overloading**: Same method name, different parameters  
### ‚úÖ **Constructor Overloading**: Same class name constructor, different parameters

---

### üî∑ Java Program:

```java
public class OverloadDemo {

    // Constructor Overloading
    public OverloadDemo() {
        System.out.println("Default Constructor");
    }

    public OverloadDemo(String name) {
        System.out.println("Constructor with one String: " + name);
    }

    public OverloadDemo(String name, int age) {
        System.out.println("Constructor with String and int: " + name + ", " + age);
    }

    // Method Overloading
    public void show() {
        System.out.println("show() with no parameters");
    }

    public void show(String msg) {
        System.out.println("show(String): " + msg);
    }

    public void show(int num) {
        System.out.println("show(int): " + num);
    }

    public void show(String msg, int count) {
        System.out.println("show(String, int): " + msg + " repeated " + count + " times");
    }

    // Main Method
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Constructor Overloading Demo
        OverloadDemo obj1 = new OverloadDemo();
        OverloadDemo obj2 = new OverloadDemo("Alice");
        OverloadDemo obj3 = new OverloadDemo("Bob", 30);

        System.out.println();

        // Method Overloading Demo
        obj1.show();
        obj1.show("Hello");
        obj1.show(100);
        obj1.show("Hi", 3);
    }
}
```

---

### üßæ **Output:**

```
Default Constructor
Constructor with one String: Alice
Constructor with String and int: Bob, 30

show() with no parameters
show(String): Hello
show(int): 100
show(String, int): Hi repeated 3 times
```

---

