### üîÅ Overriding vs Overloading in Java

These are two core **polymorphism** concepts in Java. Let‚Äôs compare them with examples üëá

---

## üü¶ **1. Method Overloading (Compile-Time Polymorphism)**

### ‚úÖ Definition:
> **Same method name**, but **different parameters** (type or number) in the **same class**.

### üîπ Example:
```java
class Calculator {
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }
}
```

### üß† Key Points:
- Happens **within the same class**
- Return type can differ, **but parameters must differ**
- Resolved at **compile time**

---

## üü® **2. Method Overriding (Runtime Polymorphism)**

### ‚úÖ Definition:
> **Subclass provides a new version** of a method that exists in its **parent class**.

### üîπ Example:
```java
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
```

### üß† Key Points:
- Happens **between superclass and subclass**
- Method name, return type, and parameters must be **exactly same**
- Resolved at **runtime**
- Requires **inheritance**

---

### üìä Overloading vs Overriding ‚Äì Summary Table

| Feature               | **Overloading**                     | **Overriding**                        |
|-----------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------------|
| Class Relationship    | Same class                          | Requires inheritance (parent-child)   |
| Method Signature      | Must be **different**               | Must be **exact same**                |
| Return Type           | Can change                          | Must be **same or covariant**         |
| Access Modifier       | No restriction                      | Can't reduce visibility               |
| Static Methods        | Can be overloaded                   | ‚ùå Can't override (they are hidden)    |
| Final Methods         | Can be overloaded                   | ‚ùå Can't override                      |
| Runtime or Compile Time | **Compile-time**                   | **Runtime**                           |

---

### ‚úÖ Example in Action:

```java
class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("A's show");
    }

    void show(String msg) {  // Overloading
        System.out.println("Message: " + msg);
    }
}

class B extends A {
    @Override
    void show() {           // Overriding
        System.out.println("B's show");
    }
}
```

