### ‚úÖ Java Code ‚Äì Manual Tree Comparison Without Built-ins or Recursion:
```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isSameTree(TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        // Create two stacks manually
        TreeNode[] stackP = new TreeNode[1000];
        TreeNode[] stackQ = new TreeNode[1000];
        int topP = -1, topQ = -1;

        while ((p != null || topP >= 0) && (q != null || topQ >= 0)) {
            // Traverse the leftmost nodes
            while (p != null && q != null) {
                stackP[++topP] = p;
                stackQ[++topQ] = q;
                p = p.left;
                q = q.left;
            }

            // If one is null and the other is not
            if (p != null || q != null) return false;

            // Pop from stacks
            p = stackP[topP--];
            q = stackQ[topQ--];

            // Compare values
            if (p.val != q.val) return false;

            // Move to right subtrees
            p = p.right;
            q = q.right;
        }

        // If one stack still has nodes, trees are not equal
        if (p != null || q != null || topP != -1 || topQ != -1) return false;

        return true;
    }
}
```

---

### üîç Key Points:
- **No recursion**
- **No built-in list or ArrayList**
- We use **fixed-size arrays as manual stacks** (`TreeNode[]`)
- We do a **manual in-order traversal** while comparing both trees node-by-node

