<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

The longest common prefix (LCP) of a group of strings must start from the first character of all strings and grow character-by-character. If at any index the characters differ across the strings, the prefix must stop there. Thus, we can compare characters at each index across all strings until we find a mismatch.

---

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

We assume the first string in the array (`strs[0]`) contains the potential longest common prefix. Then, for each character position `i` in the first string:
- Compare that character with the character at the same position in all other strings.
- If we find a mismatch or reach the end of any string, we return the substring of the first string from index `0` to `i`.
- If no mismatches are found, we return the full first string as the common prefix.

This is known as the **vertical scanning approach**.

---

# Complexity
- Time complexity:  
  $$O(n \cdot L)$$  
  Where `n` is the number of strings and `L` is the length of the first string. We compare up to `L` characters for each of the `n` strings.

- Space complexity:  
  $$O(1)$$  
  We use only a constant amount of extra space (not counting the output string). If counting the output, it is $$O(k)$$ where `k` is the length of the common prefix.

